{{Infobox person | name = Hugh Worthington | image = <!-- just the name, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1752|06|21}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{death date and age|1813|7|26|1752|6|21}} | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = [[Bunhill Fields]] | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | ethnicity = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | alma_mater = [[Daventry Academy]] | occupation = Academic and clergy | years_active = Late-18th century{{spaced ndash}}early-19th century | denomination = <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = }}
'''Hugh Worthington''' (21 June 1752 – 26 July 1813), was a British [[Arian]] divine. He was born in [[Leicester]], and studied at the [[Daventry Academy]] under [[Caleb Ashworth]]. Worthington was a pastor at [[Salters' Hall]], London, from 1782; a trustee of Dr [[Daniel Williams (theologian)|Daniel Williams]]'s foundations, 1785; and was a lecturer on classics and logic from 1786 to 1789. He published sermons and other writings.{{sfn|Lee|1903|p=1,438}}
He died on 26 July 1813, and was buried in [[Bunhill Fields]] burial ground.
