{{Infobox person | name = Jane Smisor Bastien | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = Jane Smisor | birth_date = {{Birth date|1936|01|15}} | birth_place = [[Hutchinson, Kansas]] | death_date = {{Death-date and age|27 March 2018|15 January 1936}} | death_place = [[La Jolla, California]] | occupation = Educator | religion = | signature = | spouse = Jim Bastien | children = Lisa and Lori }}
'''Jane Smisor Bastien''' is an American author and educator, best known for publishing works on teaching piano methods and techniques. She published more than 500 books that were translated into sixteen languages.
==Early life== Bastien graduated from [[Barnard College]] in 1957 and received a masters from [[Teachers College, Columbia University]]. While at Columbia, she met fellow student Neil A. Kjos Jr., who later became president of [[Neil A. Kjos Music Company]]. She met Jim Bastien in New Orleans, Louisiana and they married in 1961.
==Career== Bastien taught at [[H. Sophie Newcomb Memorial College]] at [[Tulane University]]. Bastien, along with her husband James, wrote numerous books on piano teaching.<ref>Baker-Jordan, Martha. ''Practical Piano Pedagogy: The Definitive Text for Piano Teachers and Pedagogy Students'' ([[Alfred Music|Warner Bros. Publications]], 2004), p. 171.</ref> The [[Music Teachers National Association]] awarded her the Lifetime Achievement Award in 1999 and the Citation for Leadership in 2018.
==References == {{Reflist}}
==External links== *[https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/jane-bastien Jane Bastien] NAMM Oral History Interview (2006) {{Authority control}}
{{DEFAULTSORT:Bastien, Jane Smisor}} [[Category:1936 births]] [[Category:2018 deaths]] [[Category:American women educators]] [[Category:American women writers]] [[Category:Barnard College alumni]] [[Category:People from Hutchinson, Kansas]] [[Category:Teachers College, Columbia University alumni]] [[Category:Tulane University faculty]]

{{Other uses|John Hegarty (disambiguation){{!}}John Hegarty}}
[[Image:TCD board.jpg|right|300px|thumb|John Hegarty, accompanied by the Board of Trinity College, Dublin,  announcing new scholars and fellows.]]

'''John Hegarty''' was elected 43rd [[Provost (education)|Provost]] of [[Trinity College, Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] in 2001 for a ten-year term.<ref name=currentprovost>[http://www.tcd.ie/provost/biog/ Current Provost's Biography]. Retrieved on 4 November 2009. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091016004425/http://www.tcd.ie/provost/biog/ |date=October 16, 2009 }}</ref>

==Life==
He was born in [[Claremorris]], [[County Mayo]], and was educated locally at [[St Colman's College, Claremorris|St Colman's College]].  He holds a [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] in Physics/Chemistry/Mathematics/Philosophy from [[St Patrick's College, Maynooth]], a [[Higher Diploma|HDipEd]] also from Maynooth and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] from [[National University of Ireland, Galway]].<ref name=currentprovost/>

===Later academic career===
Following a postdoctoral stay at the [[University of Wisconsin–Madison]], he was a research scientist at [[Bell Labs]], [[New Jersey]] for six years. He returned to Ireland in 1986 as Professor of Laser Physics in Trinity College. Producing over 140 publications, and developing a number of patents, he was a co-founder of Optronics Ireland and of campus company Eblana Photonics. He is a member of the [[Royal Irish Academy]], the [[American Physical Society]], the [[Optical Society of America]], the [[IEEE|Institute of Electronic and Electrical Engineers]] and Fellow of the [[Institute of Physics]].<ref name=currentprovost/>

Prior to becoming Provost, Hegarty was Dean of Research and Head of the Physics Department.<ref name=currentprovost/>

==Personal life==
Hegarty is married to Neasa Ní Chinnéide, President of the [[European Bureau for Lesser-Used Languages]],<ref>[http://www.eblul.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=33 About Us] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091201185012/http://www.eblul.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=33 |date=2009-12-01 }}. ''European Bureau for Lesser-Used Languages''. Retrieved on 4 November 2009.</ref> and they have two children, Cillian and Ciarán.<ref name=currentprovost/>

