A '''talking tactile tablet''' or '''T3''' is a [[graphic tablet]] with a touch surface that can be used as an [[input device]] that uses swell paper to create 3D overlays and connects audio files to parts of the overlays. The device is  connected to a computer and run with a programme CD, and has a tactile surface which produces touchable icons that provide audio feedback when they are pressed.<ref name=T3b>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/hereford/worcs/4782052.stm|title= College creates new touch device|work= BBC News|publisher= British Broadcasting Corporation|date= 7 March 2006|accessdate= 26 April 2010}}</ref> It can be used to help visually impaired users to interpret diagrams, charts and maps by producing a tactile, touchable image, and audio feedback.<ref name="T3">{{cite news|url= http://www.worcesternews.co.uk/archive/2007/04/19/Health+%28hereford_news_health%29/1337514.College_breaks_new_ground/|title= College breaks new ground|publisher= Worcester News|date= 18 April 2007|accessdate= 26 April 2010}}</ref>

The T3 was developed at the United Kingdom's [[Royal National College for the Blind]] in [[Hereford]] in conjunction with a software company based in the United States.<ref name="T3"/> The device was originally developed for educational purposes but is adaptable for other uses. In 2005, [[Hereford Museum and Art Gallery]] became the first in the United Kingdom to invest in the technology.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://archive.thisisherefordshire.co.uk/2005/7/25/68216.html|title= Old meets new at city attraction|publisher= Newsquest Media Ltd|work= [[Hereford Times]]|date= 25 July 2005|accessdate= 26 April 2010}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The T3 was later sold on the [[Globalization|international marketplace]] with the help of the [[UK Trade & Investment]]'s passport initiative – a scheme which gives new exporters the training, planning and support they need to succeed in overseas markets.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.herefordtimes.com/archive/2007/04/06/Business+%28wn_news_business%29/1313472.Overseas_success_for_college___s_tool_for_blind/|title= Overseas success for college's tool for blind|work= Hereford Times|publisher= Newsquest Media Ltd|first= Mike|last= Pryce|date= 6 April 2007|accessdate= 26 April 2010}}</ref>


